edback disperses molecular clouds;\nand (3) determining the mechanism driving the evolution of planet-forming disks\naround young solar-analog stars. Hyperion conducts this science using a\nstraightforward, highly-efficient, single-channel instrument design. Hyperion's\ninstrument consists of a 48 cm primary mirror, with an f/5 focal ratio. The\nspectrometer has two modes, both covering 138.5-161.5 nm bandpasses. A low\nresolution mode has a spectral resolution of R>10,000 with a slit length of 65\narcmin, while the high resolution mode has a spectral resolution of R>50,000\nover a slit length of 5 armin. Hyperion occupies a 2 week long, high-earth,\nLunar resonance TESS-like orbit, and conducts 2 weeks of planned observations\nper orbit, with time for downlinks and calibrations. Hyperion was reviewed as\nCategory I, which is the highest rating possible, but was not selected.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 13 Dec 2022 19:29:58 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-12-15"}
